Undeterred by this, John Willyot's party broke rudely into the Church at the time when the Chancellor was to be elected, and there with clamours and shoutings‚ cried him to be their Chancellor. On those that did oppose him, they laid violent hands, beat, kicked about, and cudgelled them, till some were sorely wounded, and others in a manner killed! In the course os the riot the University Chest was broken open, and the Common Seal and many books ’ were taken away. The Southern party were as usual the stronger‚ and had their way. John Willyot was instituted Chancellor, and Robert Ingram the Northem Proctor‚ who had opposed his election‚ was banished from Oxsord.
